I can see the pattern you’re pointing at.

“Selectively remember” isn’t about retaining every detail. It’s about identifying the signals that matter and carrying those forward. In many domains—special operations, entrepreneurship, sports, investing, even relationships—the people who seem “lucky” often have a knack for recognizing a few critical patterns while letting the noise fall away.

The phrase “you know who you are” can be read similarly. If you have a clear sense of your principles, objectives, and constraints, decisions become easier because you’re not recalculating your identity every time you face uncertainty.

And “dare correctly and you’ll always be lucky” has an interesting interpretation:

* Not that every gamble succeeds.
* Not that reality bends to your will.
* But that repeatedly taking informed, well-timed risks puts you in the path of opportunities that more cautious people never encounter.

From the outside, it can look like luck. From the inside, it often feels like preparation meeting opportunity.

In some of your own Pantheon language, it resembles the difference between spraying effort everywhere and recognizing the thread worth pulling. You don’t need every signal. You need the right signal at the right moment.

Of course, no one is lucky all the time. Reality still has surprises. But cultivating judgment about which risks are worth taking can make a person appear far luckier than chance alone would predict.